n and has expressed support for fiscal restraint and cutting non-essential spending.\n  - Sanctuary policy and immigration enforcement — The listener wants to know concretely which Democratic primary candidates oppose or support sanctuary-style policies, not just which ones use immigration-friendly language.\n  - June primary ballot clarity — The listener is narrowing focus to actionable primary choices and wants episode content organized around who they can actually vote for in June.\nOpen questions the listener keeps raising:\n  - Who among the Democratic primary candidates actually opposes sanctuary policy on illegal immigration?\n  - Is Andrew Friedson the candidate who stands for fiscal restriction and spending discipline?\n  - Why does MCPS want to close and move Wootton High School, and what happens next?\n  - What is Kramer's full historical voting record, including old news and public records beyond recent sessions?\n  - What are the documented policy differences between each candidate on my primary ballot?\nTopics they want more coverage of:\n  - Andrew Friedson's specific fiscal record and positions — listener asked directly and has not received a focused answer\n  - Wootton High School closure — listener asked directly; scripts acknowledged it but did not resolve it\n  - Full historical background research on candidates (old news articles, public records, career-long voting history, not just recent session votes)\n  - Concrete side-by-side policy comparison of all Democratic primary candidates across the listener's specific races\nRECENT COVERAGE TO AVOID — do NOT reuse these framings, taglines, or anecdotes (they already shipped in the last 5 days):\n  - The framing \"a listener asked us last week/earlier this week which Democratic primary candidates actually oppose sanctuary policy on illegal immigration\" used as a setup line — appears verbatim or near-verbatim in both 2026-04-28 ep1 and 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The Evan Glass bill requiring background screening for DHS agents joining Montgomery County police — introduced and framed as the concrete sanctuary-policy example in 2026-04-28 ep1 and again in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - The ICE agent mask-ban ordinance passed by the Montgomery County Council — covered as the sanctuary-policy benchmark in 2026-04-29 ep2\n  - \"Two stories, properly worked through\" / \"two stories, not spreading thin across six\" as an episode-framing device — used in 2026-04-29 ep1\n  - Governor Moore's \"Leave No One Behind\" slogan contrasted with disability services cuts — used in 2026-04-27 ep1 and ep1.rewrite\n  - The ACA marketplace quiet-downgrade story (\"thousands of Marylanders have been quietly downgrading their health insurance plans\") — introduced in 2026-04-28 ep1 and revisited in 2026-04-29 ep3\n  - Maryland's 90-day part-time legislature explanation (\"they meet in Annapolis for ninety days, the rest of the time they're lawyers, teachers, small business owners\") — used in 2026-04-26 ep3 and ep3.rewrite\n  - The wave of 25 Maryland lawmakers retiring or running for other offices framing — used in 2026-04-26 ep1, ep1.rewrite, and ep4\n  - The Beltsville Agricultural Research Center closure story as a District 19 candidate-record hook — used in 2026-04-27 ep4 and ep4.rewrite\n  - Listener's own frustration about promised candidate deep-dives not delivering — the show has now narrated this complaint back to the listener across at least five episodes; do not repeat it as a framing device again\n\nWrite the full dialogue to `output_file`. Plain text only.",
