            "raw_content": "Maryland Public Service Commission Chair Kumar Barve, in a photo from 2024. (File photo by Bryan P. Sears/Maryland Matters)    The Maryland Public Service Commission is delaying a policy that would make new gas customers pay the full cost of pipeline extensions to their properties, a proposal that had enraged natural gas companies. \n The about-face on a policy that was set last summer is among the first major decisions by the commission’s new chairman, Kumar Barve, and it caught climate groups and consumer advocates by surprise. \n But Barve said he and the other four commissioners felt they needed more information about the policy’s impact on the state’s overall economy and its housing market. Barve, a Dcmocrat who represented Montgomery County in the House of Delegates for more than 30 years, compared it to the fiscal notes lawmakers get on bills. \n “In terms of a legislative thing, we always have fiscal notes for bills, and we don&#8217;t vote on bills until we have a proper fiscal note,&#8221; he said in an interview. &#8220;I think this is the equivalent of that.” \n The utility regulating commission issued the policy change nearly a year ago under its former chair, who stepped down earlier this year  at the urging  of Maryland Gov. Wes Moore (D), who then elevated Barve to the position. \n It’s not clear how long the delay will last. But climate groups and consumer advocates, who back the policy change, are frustrated. They expected the May 8 meeting, where the delay was a",
